Below is a **single, self‑contained unit** that you can drop into the BlockSci source tree (or into a separate library) and compile as a C‑compatible shared object.  

* The public interface is a pure‑C header (`blocksci_c.h`).  
* The implementation lives in one source file (`blocksci_c.cpp`).  
* The wrapper is written in C++ but exported with `extern "C"` so that any C compiler can include the header and call the functions.  
* The design follows the “callback‑per‑item” pattern used by pandas, Polars, Arrow‑C, etc.: the hot loop lives in the library, the user‑supplied callback is invoked for each block, and the callback may abort the walk by returning a non‑zero value.  

---

## 1️⃣ Public C header – `blocksci_c.h`

```c
/*=====================================================================
  blocksci_c.h
  C binding for BlockSci – iterate over blocks and run user code.
  --------------------------------------------------------------------
  The API is deliberately tiny: create an iterator, walk it with a
  callback, and read a few cheap fields from the block view.
  All structures are opaque – the library owns the memory.
 =====================================================================*/
#ifndef BLOCKSCI_C_H
#define BLOCKSCI_C_H

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Compatibility with C++ compilers
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Opaque types – the real definitions live in the C++ implementation.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef struct bs_block_s   bs_block_t;    /* read‑only view of a block   */
typedef struct bs_iter_s    bs_iter_t;     /* iterator over the chain     */

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Callback signature.
   The library calls the user function for every block.
   *block* points to a read‑only view that stays valid until the next
   callback invocation (or until the iterator is destroyed).
   *user_data* is whatever the caller passed to bs_iterate_blocks().
   Return 0 to continue, any non‑zero value to abort the walk.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef int (*bs_block_cb)(const bs_block_t *block, void *user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Life‑time management
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* Create an iterator that walks the whole chain stored under *chain_path*.
   Returns NULL on error (e.g. path does not contain a BlockSci database). */
bs_iter_t *bs_iter_new(const char *chain_path);

/* Release all resources held by the iterator.  After this call the
   iterator must not be used again. */
void bs_iter_free(bs_iter_t *it);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   The hot‑path: walk the chain.
   The function blocks until the iterator reaches the end of the chain,
   the callback returns non‑zero, or an internal error occurs.
   Return values:
     0   – walk completed normally (all blocks visited)
    >0   – callback asked for early termination (the same value is
           propagated to the caller)
    <0   – internal error (e.g. corrupted DB).  The iterator is still
           usable afterwards, but the walk stopped early.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int bs_iterate_blocks(bs_iter_t *it, bs_block_cb cb, void *user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Accessors – cheap, in‑line reads from the current block view.
   All pointers returned (e.g. hash) are owned by the iterator and stay
   valid until the next callback or iterator destruction.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
uint32_t bs_block_height(const bs_block_t *blk);
uint64_t bs_block_timestamp(const bs_block_t *blk);
const char *bs_block_hash_hex(const bs_block_t *blk);   /* 64‑char hex string */
size_t   bs_block_tx_count(const bs_block_t *blk);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Optional: a helper that returns the raw pointer to the underlying
   BlockSci C++ object.  Exposed only for advanced use; it is NOT part of
   the stable ABI.  Users should stick to the accessor functions above.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#ifdef BLOCKSCI_C_EXPOSE_INTERNALS
void *bs_block_internal_ptr(const bs_block_t *blk);
#endif

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   End of extern "C"
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#ifdef __cplusplus
}
#endif

#endif /* BLOCKSCI_C_H */
```

