## 3️⃣ How a C programmer would use the API

```c
/*--------------------------------------------------------------
   example.c – client code written in pure C
  --------------------------------------------------------------*/
#include "blocksci_c.h"
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int print_block(const bs_block_t *blk, void *user) {
    (void)user;               // unused in this simple example
    uint32_t  h   = bs_block_height(blk);
    uint64_t  ts  = bs_block_timestamp(blk);
    const char *hash = bs_block_hash_hex(blk);
    size_t    ntx = bs_block_tx_count(blk);

    printf("height=%u  time=%" PRIu64 "  hash=%s  txes=%zu\n",
           h, ts, hash, ntx);

    /* Continue walking – return 0.
       Return >0 to stop early, <0 to signal an error. */
    return 0;
}

int main(void) {
    const char *chain_path = "/path/to/blocksci/chain";

    bs_iter_t *it = bs_iter_new(chain_path);
    if (!it) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to open chain at %s\n", chain_path);
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    int rc = bs_iterate_blocks(it, print_block, NULL);
    if (rc != 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Iteration stopped with rc=%d\n", rc);
    }

    bs_iter_free(it);
    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

Compile the library and the example (Linux example shown):

```bash
# Build the binding (requires a C++17 compiler and BlockSci headers/libs)
g++ -std=c++17 -fPIC -shared -o libblocksci_c.so blocksci_c.cpp -lblocksci

# Build the user program
gcc -o example example.c -L. -lblocksci_c -lblocksci -pthread
```

Running `./example` will stream one line per block (≈ 800 M lines for the full chain) while keeping the hot loop inside the C++ library, guaranteeing that the per‑block callback overhead is limited to a single function call and a few cheap field accesses.

---

## 4️⃣ Why this design is fast and safe

| Concern | Design decision |
|---------|-----------------|
| **Zero‑allocation per block** | The iterator re‑uses a single `bs_block_s` view; the callback receives a pointer to that view, not a freshly allocated object. |
| **No copying of block data** | The view stores a raw pointer to the internal `blocksci::Block`. Accessors read directly from that object (or from a tiny thread‑local buffer for the hex hash). |
| **Callback overhead minimal** | The hot loop is a simple `for` over the native C++ iterator, with only one indirect call (`cb`) per block. |
| **Early abort** | The callback can return a positive integer to stop the walk immediately – useful for searches or sampling. |
| **C ABI stability** | All exported symbols are plain C functions; the opaque structs hide implementation details, so you can change the internals without breaking user code. |
| **Thread‑safety** | Each iterator is independent; the library does not use any global mutable state. Users may create multiple iterators in different threads. |
| **Error handling** | Internal C++ exceptions are caught and turned into negative error codes; the API never throws across the C boundary. |
| **Ease of use** | The header mirrors the style of pandas/Polars “apply” APIs: *create → iterate with callback → free*. |

Feel free to extend the header with more accessor functions (e.g. transaction iterators, block size, difficulty) – the pattern stays the same: expose cheap getters that read from the underlying `blocksci::Block` without allocating. This binding gives C developers the same ergonomic “run my code on every row” experience that data‑frame libraries provide, while preserving the high‑throughput performance BlockSci is built for.
